          <msContents>
            <summary>
                        6 fol. on parchment; Shelfmark: Arabe 324 a; Qurʾānic Text: Q  3:104-113, Q 3: 120-133, Q 3: 180-187, Q 4:3-9, Q 4: 24-29, Q 4: 36-42; Lines per page: 12; Script style: kūfī type C;  Dimensions: 470 x 565 mm; Estimated date of production: possibly a production of the time after 1000. <p>The catalogue of the Qurʾānic manuscripts of the French National Library (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/5RF6W5GJ">Déroche, 1983: p. 143</ref>) gives the following information: "Arabe <hi rend="bold">324 a</hi>  : ffo 1 et 2, 4 et 5, 7 et 8.   Fo l : III, 104-113 ; fo 2 : III,  120-133; fo 4 : III, 180-187; fo 5 : IV, 3-9; fo 7 : IV, 24-29 ; fo 8 :  IV, 36-42.    Copie anonyme et non datée. Graphie non classée. Le  contour des lettres a été dessiné puis rempli d’encre. Diacritiques  rares; vocalisation absente. Une main plus récente a ajouté à l’encre  noire, à la première et à la dernière ligne de chaque feuillet, la  transcription en écriture cursive du début et de la ﬁn du texte. Les  versets sont séparés par des rosettes de type 3.1.2 ; des médaillons de  type 3.A.II à l'intérieur desquels est écrit <hi rend="italic">ḫams</hi> ou <hi rend="italic">ʿašr</hi>  indiquent les groupes de cinq ou dix versets.  Parchemin. 6 feuillets.  Page : 540 x 618. 12 lignes. Réglure à l'encre au ro et au vo de chaque  feuillet. Encre brune. Surface d’écriture : 470 x 565.  A rapprocher du  ms. Caire Masāḥif 139 (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/MMPRD8Z2" sameAs="MMPRD8Z2" type="zotero">Vom Papyrus zum Codex, Der Beitrag Ägyptens zur Buchkultur, Leipzig 1970</ref>, p. 95 et pl. 114)." Script style of the six leaves is given as non classified ("graphie non classée") but shows similiarities to styles of group C. It is possible that <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/3/verse/104/manuscripts/786/page/1r">Arabe 324a</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/3/vers/139?handschrift=787">Arabe 324 (b)</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/4/vers/122?handschrift=24">Arabe 324 (c)</ref> and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/35/vers/36?handschrift=788">Arabe 324 (d)</ref>, together with a large codex fragment kept in Cairo (<ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/37/verse/175/manuscripts/340/page/1r">tables 1-12</ref> reproduced in <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/ZZZEKDZ7" sameAs="ZZZEKDZ7" type="zotero">Moritz' Arabic Paleography 1905</ref>, leaves that are today apparently registered under shelfmark <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/10/verse/59/manuscripts/376/page/1r">maṣāḥif 139 </ref>in the Egyptian National Library),  <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/43/verse/52/manuscripts/171/page/1r">Gotha ms. orient. A 462</ref> and leaves in Istanbul (Türk ve Islam Esereleri Müzesi) were originally from the same codex, see overview in entry <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/43/verse/52/manuscripts/171/page/1r">Gotha ms. orient. A 462</ref>.</p><p>Datation: Although the script style kūfī C in the typology of François Déroche <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/KCAZQ5NS">(Déroche 1983: p. 75-77)</ref> suggests a production date in the early period, this fragment could also be a production of a more recent recent period. It is noteworthy that the text of the Gotha folios, acquired by Ulrich Jasper von Seetzen (1767-1811), overlaps with the folio kept by the <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/1599">Detroit Institute of Art 30.317</ref>. However, since the manuscript "maṣāḥif 139" is not accessible, an important point of evidence is still missing. As Aleksey Shebunin (1867-1937) in his article <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/MVUHA7W6">Куфический Коран Хедивской Библиотеки в Каире</ref>, ("The kufic Qurʾān in the Khedival Library in Cairo”) mentions 248 leaves of the original codex, 34 folios (parchment) written by a later scribe, 61 leaves of other parchment Qurʾāns as replacement of missing folios it is possible that fragments have been produced considerably later than the 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> century perhaps in order to replace damaged or lost leaves. Carbon dating of samples from the Paris fragments Arabe 324 (a), Arabe 324 (c) and 324 (d) supports this idea. Eléonore Cellard mentions in a <ref target="https://twitter.com/CellardEleonore/status/1213439294024630273">twitter message on January 4, 2020</ref> that carbon dating of samples from Arabe 324a, Arabe 324c and Arabe 324d gives the following results: “…Ar.324c (between 660-780). The others are later: Ar.324a is from the 11th-12th, and 324d is from the beginning of the 12th- beginning of the 13th” ( t<ref target="https://twitter.com/CellardEleonore/status/1213439294024630273">witter message on January 20, 2020</ref>). Based on this evidence fragments Paris <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/4/vers/122?handschrift=24">Arabe 324 (c)</ref> and Gotha <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/verse-navigator/sura/43/verse/52/manuscripts/171/page/1r">Ms. orient. A 462</ref> are to be considered as leaves of the original codex, whereas Paris <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/3/vers/104?handschrift=786">Arabe 324 (a)</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/de/manuscripts/787/page/3r?sura=3&amp;verse=139">Arabe 324 (b)</ref> and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/35/vers/36?handschrift=788">Arabe 324 (d)</ref>, are likely supposed to be pages that have been produced much later.</p>
                    </summary>
